    readingMinutes: 4,
    category: 'tipping',
    country: 'Czech Republic',
    countrySlug: 'czech-republic',
    content: [
      { type: 'intro', body: 'The Czech Republic has a clear tipping culture, particularly in Prague. At sit-down restaurants and bars with table service, a 10% tip is standard and expected. Service workers earn a modest base wage and rely on tips as part of their income. The Czech Koruna (CZK) makes rounding up intuitive — tip in cash when possible, directly to your server.' },
      { type: 'h2', heading: 'Tipping in the Czech Republic at a Glance' },
      { type: 'table', rows: [
        { label: 'Restaurants', value: '10% for good service — standard in Prague and tourist cities' },
        { label: 'Beer Halls (Pivnice)', value: 'Round up per round — CZK 5–10 per beer' },
        { label: 'Taxis', value: 'Round up to nearest 20 CZK — 10% appreciated' },
        { label: 'Hotel Porters', value: 'CZK 40–80 per bag' },
        { label: 'Hotel Housekeeping', value: 'CZK 50–100 per stay' },
        { label: 'Tour Guides', value: 'CZK 100–200 for a walking tour; more for private' },
        { label: 'Food Delivery', value: 'CZK 20–50 appreciated' },
      ]},
      { type: 'h2', heading: 'Restaurants & Beer Halls' },
      { type: 'p', body: 'Prague is one of Europe\'s great restaurant and beer cities, and tipping is woven into the culture. At restaurants, tell the server the total you wish to pay when settling — if the bill is CZK 780, you might say "800" to leave a CZK 20 tip, or "850" for a more generous gratuity. At traditional pivnice (Czech beer halls), the custom is to tab-run through the evening with a waiter marking a slip at your table — leave a small tip per round (CZK 5–10 per beer) or round up the final tab by 10%. In tourist-heavy areas of Prague\'s Old Town, some restaurants have begun adding service charges — always check the bill before adding extra.' },
      { type: 'h2', heading: 'Taxis & Getting Around Prague' },
      { type: 'p', body: 'Taxis in Prague have a mixed reputation, and tourist-facing cabs near Old Town Square sometimes overcharge. Use a ride-hailing app (Bolt is dominant in Prague) rather than hailing a cab on the street — you will see the price upfront. For Bolt rides, round up or tip 10% in-app. The Prague Metro and trams are excellent and cheap for most journeys.' },
      { type: 'warning', body: 'Prague has a history of taxi overcharging at tourist hotspots. Never take an unmarked cab and always use Bolt or Uber where possible. A legitimate metered taxi from the airport to central Prague should cost CZK 500–700 — if quoted significantly more, decline.' },
      { type: 'h2', heading: 'Frequently Asked Questions' },
      { type: 'faq', faqs: [
        { q: 'Do you tip in Prague?', a: 'Yes — 10% is standard at restaurants with table service. This is a genuine expectation, not just a courtesy.' },
        { q: 'What currency do I use to tip in Czech Republic?', a: 'Czech Koruna (CZK). The Czech Republic is not in the eurozone — euros are not widely accepted outside of airports and some hotels.' },
        { q: 'Should I tip at a Prague beer hall?', a: 'Yes — round up per round or add 10% to the final tab. The waiter tracks your drinks on a slip; tip when you settle up.' },
      ]},
    ],
